":\"3. The workflow runs on GitHub’s schedule, pulls your repo, then SSHes into the phone and executes the same \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"run_my_job.sh\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" you used in Termux.\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"**Pros:** No battery‑saving worries, runs even if your phone is off (as long as the tunnel stays up).  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"**Cons:** Requires a always‑on server or a VPS, plus a bit of networking setup.\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"---\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"## 6️⃣ Summary of trade‑offs\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"| Method | Runs on phone? | Needs external server? | Battery impact | Setup effort | Reliability |\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"|--------|----------------|------------------------|----------------|--------------|-------------|\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"| **Termux + \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"termux-job-scheduler\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (unless you want remote logs) | Low (runs only at scheduled minute) | Low‑moderate (install Termux, add script) | Good for simple daily/weekly jobs; survives reboot with \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"Termux:Boot\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". |\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"| **Tasker** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | Low‑moderate (foreground service may keep CPU awake) | Low (GUI only) | Good for quick tasks, but may be killed on newer Android versions. |\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"| **GitHub Actions / Cloud scheduler** | ❌ No (but can trigger phone) | ✅ Yes (VPS or GitHub) | None on phone (phone only wakes when it receives a request) | Moderate‑high (networking, secrets) | Very reliable, works 24/7 regardless of phone state. |\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"| **Cron on a VPS + SSH to phone** | ❌ No (but can push to phone) | ✅ Yes | None | Moderate | Similar to cloud, but you control the cron. |\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Pick the one that matches **how often you need it, how much you want to rely on the phone’s battery**, and how comfortable you are with the command line.\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"---\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"## 7️⃣ Quick checklist for “just get something working today”\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"1. **Install Termux** (F‑Droid).  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"2. **Install \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"termux-job-scheduler\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"** \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"pkg install termux-tools\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"3. **Copy your workflow script** into \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"~/workflows/\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"4. **Create a wrapper** that logs output.  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"5. **Register a daily job** with \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"termux-job-scheduler\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"6. **Add a boot‑complete script** \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"~/.termux/boot/…\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") to re‑register the job after reboots.  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"7. **Test it manually**: run the wrapper script once, check the log file.  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"8. **Reboot** the phone and verify the job appears again \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"termux-job-scheduler --list\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"If it works, you now have a **self‑contained scheduled runner** on your Android device that will execute your workflow automatically at the time you chose—no external server required.\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"---\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"### Need more help?\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"- **If your workflow needs network access** (e.g., pulling from a private Git repo), make sure Termux has the needed permissions \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"termux-setup-storage\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"termux-wake-lock\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"- **If you want to push results back to GitHub** after the run, you can add \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"git push\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" inside the script; just store a **personal access token** in \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"~/.git-credentials\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (chmod 600).  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"- **If you hit “Job scheduler not firing”** after a reboot, double‑check that \"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"code\"}],\"text\":\"Termux:Boot\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is installed and that the re‑registration script is executable.  \"},{\"type\":\"hardBreak\"}]}]}","title":"Scheduled task: termux+claude code cli","tags":["ai"],"updateTime":1770776040218,"createTime":1770776038379,"draft":false,"intro":"### Short answer  Yes – you can have a **self‑hosted “run” of a workflow on your Android device on a schedule**, but you’ll need to use a tool that can execute code on Android on a regular timer (e.g. **Termux + cron**, **Tasker**, or a **cloud‑based runner**).  The most reliable way is to **off‑load the scheduled execution to a separate machine that can reach your repo** (e.g. a cheap VPS, GitHub Actions, or a Raspberry Pi) and let it trigger the workflow on your device only when you need it.  Below you’ll find three practical paths, the pros/cons of each, and concrete step‑by‑step instructions for the one most likely to work out‑of‑the‑box on an Android phone: **run a tiny “scheduler” inside Termux**.---## 1️⃣ Why Android isn’t a natural host for scheduled jobs| Limitation | What it means for you ||------------|-----------------------|| **No native cron** | Android’s init system (init.rc) doesn’t expose a user‑level scheduler. || **Background execution limits** | Starting with Android 12 the OS aggressively kills background processes; a script that just sleeps won’t survive reboots or Doze mode. || **No persistent system services** | You can’t register a BroadcastReceiver that fires at a fixed wall‑clock time without user interaction (unless the app is a foreground service or uses WorkManager). || **No built‑in systemd** | Systemd‑style timers are unavailable. |That’s why most people who want real scheduled automation on Android rely on **Termux** (a Linux‑like environment) or **Tasker** (a UI‑driven automation app).  Both can schedule commands, but they have trade‑offs (see the table later).---## 2️⃣ Three practical ways to run a scheduled workflow| Approach | Where the scheduled trigger lives | Where the actual workflow runs | Setup complexity | Typical use‑case ||----------|----------------------------------|--------------------------------|------------------|-----------------|| **A. Termux + cron (or termux-job-scheduler)** | Inside Termux on the phone itself | Directly on the phone (calls your repo) | Low‑moderate (install Termux, add a script, enable scheduler) | You want the job to run on the phone (e.g., lint, test, push a notification). || **B. Tasker (or Automate) → adbTermux** | Tasker’s built‑in scheduler | Same as A, but Tasker can use UI tricks to keep the script alive | Low (no terminal knowledge needed) | You already use Tasker for other phone automations and want a quick “run every night” job. || **C. Off‑load to a remote scheduler (GitHub Actions, a cheap VPS, or a Raspberry Pi)** | Remote cloud / server (cron, GitHub schedule) | Runs on the remote host, optionally triggers your phone via SSH or an API | Moderate‑high (need external infra) | You need a reliable, always‑on schedule that survives reboots, battery‑saving, etc. |### TL;DR – The easiest “phone‑only” solution  **Termux + termux-job-scheduler** (a wrapper that works even when the app is in the background).  It lets you register a one‑off or repeating job that executes a script at a specific wall‑clock time or interval.---## 3️⃣ Detailed walkthrough – Scheduling with Termux> **Prerequisites**  >  Android 8+ (most modern phones)  >  Root is **not** required  >  You have git credentials (PAT or SSH key) already stored in Termux if you need to git pullpush.### 3.1 Install Termux & required packages1. *Install from F-Droid** (recommended, always up‑to‑date):     ```bash   pkg install termux-api  # optional, gives access to notifications / vibration   ```2. **Open Termux and run:**   ```bash   pkg update && pkg upgrade -y   pkg install git python clang python-dev  # plus whatever you need for your workflow   pkg install termux-tools   # provides termux-job-scheduler   ```### 3.2 Put your workflow script somewhereAssume your workflow is a Python script ~/workflows/my_job.py that you want to run every day at 02:30 AM.```bashmkdir -p ~/workflowscat > ~/workflows/my_job.py <<'EOF'#!/usr/bin/env python3import os, sys, subprocess, datetime, json# Example: pull latest changes, run tests, commit & pushdef main():    os.chdir(os.path.expanduser('~/my-repo'))   # <-- your repo folder    subprocess.run(['git', 'pull'], check=True)    # ... your test / lint commands here ...    subprocess.run(['git', 'add', '.'], check=True)    subprocess.run(['git', 'commit', '-m', f'Scheduled run {datetime.datetime.now()}'], check=False)    subprocess.run(['git', 'push'], check=False)if name == '__main__':    main()EOFchmod +x ~/workflows/my_job.py```### 3.3 Create a tiny wrapper script that the scheduler will call```bashcat > ~/workflows/run_my_job.sh <<'EOF'#!/data/data/com.termux/files/usr/bin/bash# This script is executed by termux-job-scheduler# It just calls your actual job script and logs the output.LOG=~/workflows/run_my_job.log{    echo \"=== $(date) ===\"    ~/workflows/my_job.py} >>\"$LOG\" 2>&1EOFchmod +x ~/workflows/run_my_job.sh```### 3.4 Register the job with termux-job-schedulertermux-job-scheduler lets you schedule **repeating** jobs using a job id and a cron‑like spec.```bash# Example: run every day at 02:30 (24‑hour clock)termux-job-scheduler --schedule \"30 2 * * *\"# The command after -- is what will be executed when the time arrivestermux-job-scheduler --job-id my_daily_job --schedule \"30 2 * * \" --command \"/data/data/com.termux/files/home/workflows/run_my_job.sh\"```> *What just happened?**  >  termux-job-scheduler registers a one‑time* job that will fire at the next occurrence of the cron expression.  >  When the job fires, the scheduler launches your wrapper script run_my_job.sh).  >  The wrapper appends a timestamp and the script’s stdout/stderr to a log file so you can debug later.### 3.5 Verify that the job is registered```bashtermux-job-scheduler --list# Should show something like:#   ID      | Command                                 | Next run time#   ---------------------------------------------------------------#   my_daily_job | /data/data/.../workflows/run_my_job.sh | 2026‑02‑12 02:30:00```### 3.6 Let the job survive rebootstermux-job-scheduler automatically re‑registers itself after a reboot **if you add it to Termux’s “boot‑completed” receiver**. The easiest way is to install the **Termux:Boot** add‑on from F‑Droid:1. Install **Termux:Boot**.  2. In Termux, run:   ```bash   termux-wake-lock   # keep CPU awake while the job runs   ```3. The ~/.termux/boot/ directory is executed on every boot, so you can place a small “re‑register” script there:   ```bash   cat > ~/.termux/boot/reschedule_my_job.sh <<'EOF'   #!/data/data/com.termux/files/usr/bin/bash   termux-job-scheduler --job-id my_daily_job --schedule \"30 2 * * \" --command \"/data/data/com.termux/files/home/workflows/run_my_job.sh\"   EOF   chmod +x ~/.termux/boot/reschedule_my_job.sh   ```Now, after each device reboot, the scheduler will re‑create the 02:30 job automatically.---## 4️⃣ Alternative: Using *Tasker** (no terminal needed)If you’d rather stay inside a graphical automation app:| Step | Action ||------|--------|| 1. Install **Tasker** (paid) and **AutoTools** (free plugin) or **Termux** as an Execute Shell action. || 2. Create a Profile → Time → set the desired start/end time (e.g., 02:30, repeat daily). || 3. In the Task → Run Shell → am startservice -n com.termux/.service.TermuxService --es \"cmd\" \"run_my_job.sh\" (or directly call your script). || 4. Enable Run As Root only if your script needs elevated permissions (generally not needed). || 5. Optionally add a Notify action to let you know when it finished. |**Pros:** No command‑line setup, visual UI, works even if you never open Termux.  **Cons:** Tasker’s free version can’t run background services reliably on Android 12+, and the UI can be a bit finicky for complex logic.---## 5️⃣ Alternative: Off‑load to **GitHub Actions** (cloud scheduler)If you’re comfortable pushing the trigger to GitHub, you can let GitHub’s built‑in scheduler run the workflow for you, and optionally have it **SSH into your phone** (via a reverse‑ssh tunnel) or **push a notification** back to you.### Example: a daily GitHub Actions workflow```yaml# .github/workflows/daily-schedule.ymlname: Daily Android Runon:  schedule:    - cron: '30 2 * * '   # 02:30 UTC every day  workflow_dispatch:      # optional manual triggerjobs:  run-on-phone:    runs-on: ubuntu-latest    steps:      - name: Checkout repo        uses: actions/checkout@v4      - name: Install termux-api (if you want to notify)        run: |          sudo apt-get update          sudo apt-get install -y openssh-client      - name: SSH to your phone (requires you to expose a reverse SSH tunnel)        env:          SSH_PRIVATE_KEY: ${{ secrets.SSH_PRIVATE_KEY }}        run: |          # Assuming you have a VPS that keeps a persistent SSH tunnel to your phone          ssh -i /tmp/key -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no user@YOUR_PHONE_IP \"cd /path/to/repo && ./run_my_job.sh\"```*How to make it work:**  1. **Expose a stable endpoint** on your phone (e.g., a reverse SSH tunnel from a cheap VPS).  2. Store the private key as a GitHub secret SSH_PRIVATE_KEY).  3. The workflow runs on GitHub’s schedule, pulls your repo, then SSHes into the phone and executes the same run_my_job.sh you used in Termux.**Pros:** No battery‑saving worries, runs even if your phone is off (as long as the tunnel stays up).  **Cons:** Requires a always‑on server or a VPS, plus a bit of networking setup.---## 6️⃣ Summary of trade‑offs| Method | Runs on phone? | Needs external server? | Battery impact | Setup effort | Reliability ||--------|----------------|------------------------|----------------|--------------|-------------|| **Termux + termux-job-scheduler** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (unless you want remote logs) | Low (runs only at scheduled minute) | Low‑moderate (install Termux, add script) | Good for simple daily/weekly jobs; survives reboot with Termux:Boot. || **Tasker** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | Low‑moderate (foreground service may keep CPU awake) | Low (GUI only) | Good for quick tasks, but may be killed on newer Android versions. || **GitHub Actions / Cloud scheduler** | ❌ No (but can trigger phone) | ✅ Yes (VPS or GitHub) | None on phone (phone only wakes when it receives a request) | Moderate‑high (networking, secrets) | Very reliable, works 24/7 regardless of phone state. || **Cron on a VPS + SSH to phone** | ❌ No (but can push to phone) | ✅ Yes | None | Moderate | Similar to cloud, but you control the cron. |Pick the one that matches **how often you need it, how much you want to rely on the phone’s battery**, and how comfortable you are with the command line.---## 7️⃣ Quick checklist for “just get something working today”1. **Install Termux** (F‑Droid).  2. **Install termux-job-scheduler** pkg install termux-tools).  3. **Copy your workflow script** into ~/workflows/.  4. **Create a wrapper** that logs output.  5. **Register a daily job** with termux-job-scheduler.  6. **Add a boot‑complete script** ~/.termux/boot/…) to re‑register the job after reboots.  7. **Test it manually**: run the wrapper script once, check the log file.  8. **Reboot** the phone and verify the job appears again termux-job-scheduler --list).  If it works, you now have a **self‑contained scheduled runner** on your Android device that will execute your workflow automatically at the time you chose—no external server required.---### Need more help?- **If your workflow needs network access** (e.g., pulling from a private Git repo), make sure Termux has the needed permissions termux-setup-storage, termux-wake-lock).  - **If you want to push results back to GitHub** after the run, you can add git push inside the script; just store a **personal access token** in ~/.git-credentials (chmod 600).  - **If you hit “Job scheduler not firing”** after a reboot, double‑check that Termux:Boot is installed and that the re‑registration script is executable.  ","html":"<h1 level=\"1\" id=\"Scheduled-task-termuxclaude-code-cli\">Scheduled task: termux+claude code cli</h1><p><br>### Short answer  <br>Yes – you can have a **self‑hosted “run” of a workflow on your Android device on a schedule**, but you’ll need to use a tool that can execute code on Android on a regular timer (e.g. **Termux + cron**, **Tasker**, or a **cloud‑based runner**).  <br>The most reliable way is to **off‑load the scheduled execution to a separate machine that can reach your repo** (e.g. a cheap VPS, GitHub Actions, or a Raspberry Pi) and let it trigger the workflow on your device only when you need it.  <br><br>Below you’ll find three practical paths, the pros/cons of each, and concrete step‑by‑step instructions for the one most likely to work out‑of‑the‑box on an Android phone: **run a tiny “scheduler” inside Termux**.<br><br>---<br><br>## 1️⃣ Why Android isn’t a natural host for scheduled jobs<br><br>| Limitation | What it means for you |<br>|------------|-----------------------|<br>| **No native <code>cron</code>** | Android’s init system (init.rc) doesn’t expose a user‑level scheduler. |<br>| **Background execution limits** | Starting with Android 12 the OS aggressively kills background processes; a script that just sleeps won’t survive reboots or Doze mode. |<br>| **No persistent system services** | You can’t register a <code>BroadcastReceiver</code> that fires at a fixed wall‑clock time without user interaction (unless the app is a foreground service or uses <code>WorkManager</code>). |<br>| **No built‑in <code>systemd</code>** | Systemd‑style timers are unavailable. |<br><br>That’s why most people who want <em>real</em> scheduled automation on Android rely on **Termux** (a Linux‑like environment) or **Tasker** (a UI‑driven automation app).  <br>Both can schedule commands, but they have trade‑offs (see the table later).<br><br>---<br><br>## 2️⃣ Three practical ways to run a scheduled workflow<br><br>| Approach | Where the scheduled trigger lives | Where the actual workflow runs | Setup complexity | Typical use‑case |<br>|----------|----------------------------------|--------------------------------|------------------|-----------------|<br>| **A. Termux + cron (or <code>termux-job-scheduler</code>)** | Inside Termux on the phone itself | Directly on the phone (calls your repo) | Low‑moderate (install Termux, add a script, enable scheduler) | You want the job to run <em>on the phone</em> (e.g., lint, test, push a notification). |<br>| **B. Tasker (or Automate) → <code>adbTermux</code>** | Tasker’s built‑in scheduler | Same as A, but Tasker can use UI tricks to keep the script alive | Low (no terminal knowledge needed) | You already use Tasker for other phone automations and want a quick “run every night” job. |<br>| **C. Off‑load to a remote scheduler (GitHub Actions, a cheap VPS, or a Raspberry Pi)** | Remote cloud / server (cron, GitHub schedule) | Runs on the remote host, optionally triggers your phone via SSH or an API | Moderate‑high (need external infra) | You need a reliable, always‑on schedule that survives reboots, battery‑saving, etc. |<br><br>### TL;DR – The easiest “phone‑only” solution  <br>**Termux + <code>termux-job-scheduler</code>** (a wrapper that works even when the app is in the background).  <br>It lets you register a <em>one‑off</em> or <em>repeating</em> job that executes a script at a specific wall‑clock time or interval.<br><br>---<br><br>## 3️⃣ Detailed walkthrough – Scheduling with Termux<br><br>&gt; **Prerequisites**  <br>&gt; <em> Android 8+ (most modern phones)  <br>&gt; </em> Root is **not** required  <br>&gt; <em> You have </em><code>git</code><em> credentials (PAT or SSH key) already stored in Termux if you need to </em><code>git pullpush</code><em>.<br><br>### 3.1 Install Termux &amp; required packages<br><br>1. </em>*Install from F-Droid** (recommended, always up‑to‑date):  <br>   ```bash<br>   pkg install termux-api  # optional, gives access to notifications / vibration<br>   ```<br>2. **Open Termux and run:**<br>   ```bash<br>   pkg update &amp;&amp; pkg upgrade -y<br>   pkg install git python clang python-dev  # plus whatever you need for your workflow<br>   pkg install termux-tools   # provides <code>termux-job-scheduler</code><br>   ```<br><br>### 3.2 Put your workflow script somewhere<br><br>Assume your workflow is a Python script <code>~/workflows/my_job.py</code> that you want to run every day at 02:30 AM.<br><br>```bash<br>mkdir -p ~/workflows<br>cat &gt; ~/workflows/my_<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"http://job.py\">job.py</a> &lt;&lt;&apos;EOF&apos;<br>#!/usr/bin/env python3<br>import os, sys, subprocess, datetime, json<br><br># Example: pull latest changes, run tests, commit &amp; push<br>def main():<br>    os.chdir(os.path.expanduser(&apos;~/my-repo&apos;))   # &lt;-- your repo folder<br>    <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"http://subprocess.run\">subprocess.run</a>([&apos;git&apos;, &apos;pull&apos;], check=True)<br>    # ... your test / lint commands here ...<br>    <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"http://subprocess.run\">subprocess.run</a>([&apos;git&apos;, &apos;add&apos;, &apos;.&apos;], check=True)<br>    <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"http://subprocess.run\">subprocess.run</a>([&apos;git&apos;, &apos;commit&apos;, &apos;-m&apos;, f&apos;Scheduled run {<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"http://datetime.datetime.now\">datetime.datetime.now</a>()}&apos;], check=False)<br>    <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"http://subprocess.run\">subprocess.run</a>([&apos;git&apos;, &apos;push&apos;], check=False)<br><br>if <strong>name</strong> == &apos;__main__&apos;:<br>    main()<br>EOF<br>chmod +x ~/workflows/my_<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"http://job.py\">job.py</a><br>```<br><br>### 3.3 Create a tiny wrapper script that the scheduler will call<br><br>```bash<br>cat &gt; ~/workflows/run_my_<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"http://job.sh\">job.sh</a> &lt;&lt;&apos;EOF&apos;<br>#!/data/data/com.termux/files/usr/bin/bash<br># This script is executed by termux-job-scheduler<br># It just calls your actual job script and logs the output.<br><br>LOG=~/workflows/run_my_job.log<br>{<br>    echo &quot;=== $(date) ===&quot;<br>    ~/workflows/my_<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"http://job.py\">job.py</a><br>} &gt;&gt;&quot;$LOG&quot; 2&gt;&amp;1<br>EOF<br>chmod +x ~/workflows/run_my_<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"http://job.sh\">job.sh</a><br>```<br><br>### 3.4 Register the job with <code>termux-job-scheduler</code><br><code>termux-job-scheduler</code> lets you schedule **repeating** jobs using a <em>job id</em> and a <em>cron‑like</em> spec.<br><br>```bash<br># Example: run every day at 02:30 (24‑hour clock)<br>termux-job-scheduler --schedule &quot;30 2 * * *&quot;<br># The command after <code>--</code> is what will be executed when the time arrives<br>termux-job-scheduler --job-id my_daily_job --schedule &quot;30 2 * * <em>&quot; --command &quot;/data/data/com.termux/files/home/workflows/run_my_</em><a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer nofollow\" href=\"http://job.sh\"><em>job.sh</em></a><em>&quot;<br>```<br><br>&gt; </em>*What just happened?**  <br>&gt; <em> </em><code>termux-job-scheduler</code><em> registers a </em>one‑time* job that will fire at the next occurrence of the cron expression.  <br>&gt; <em> When the job fires, the scheduler launches your wrapper script </em><code>run_my_job.sh</code><em>).  <br>&gt; </em> The wrapper appends a timestamp and the script’s stdout/stderr to a log file so you can debug later.<br><br>### 3.5 Verify that the job is registered<br><br>```bash<br>ter