 7️⃣ Quick checklist for “just get something working today”<br><br>1. **Install Termux** (F‑Droid).  <br>2. **Install <code>termux-job-scheduler</code>** <code>pkg install termux-tools</code>).  <br>3. **Copy your workflow script** into <code>~/workflows/</code>.  <br>4. **Create a wrapper** that logs output.  <br>5. **Register a daily job** with <code>termux-job-scheduler</code>.  <br>6. **Add a boot‑complete script** <code>~/.termux/boot/…</code>) to re‑register the job after reboots.  <br>7. **Test it manually**: run the wrapper script once, check the log file.  <br>8. **Reboot** the phone and verify the job appears again <code>termux-job-scheduler --list</code>).  <br><br>If it works, you now have a **self‑contained scheduled runner** on your Android device that will execute your workflow automatically at the time you chose—no external server required.<br><br>---<br><br>### Need more help?<br><br>- **If your workflow needs network access** (e.g., pulling from a private Git repo), make sure Termux has the needed permissions <code>termux-setup-storage</code>, <code>termux-wake-lock</code>).  <br>- **If you want to push results back to GitHub** after the run, you can add <code>git push</code> inside the script; just store a **personal access token** in <code>~/.git-credentials</code> (chmod 600).  <br>- **If you hit “Job scheduler not firing”** after a reboot, double‑check that <code>Termux:Boot</code> is installed and that the re‑registration script is executable.  <br></p><script type=\"module\">const injectHtml = (root, html) => {\n  const iframe = document.createElement(\"iframe\");\n  const htmlContent = `<html><head></head><body>${html}</body></html>`;\n  iframe.style.width = \"100%\";\n  iframe.style.height = \"100%\";\n  iframe.onload = () => {\n    const doc = iframe.contentDocument || iframe.contentWindow?.document;\n    if (!doc) {\n      return;\n    }\n    doc.open();\n    doc.write(htmlContent);\n    doc.close();\n  };\n  root.replaceChildren(iframe);